abstract: For most people, it’s the click that brings a package to their door. But a look at Baltimore shows how Amazon may now reach into Americans’ daily existence in more ways than any corporation in history.
snippet: For most people, it’s the click that brings a package to their door. But a look at Baltimore shows how Amazon may now reach into Americans’ daily existence in more ways than any corporation in history.
lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — Another big Prime Air 767 takes off from Baltimore-Washington International Airport — where Amazon’s shipping last year eclipsed that of FedEx and U.P.S. put together — and wheels above the old industrial city. Below, the online giant seems to touch every niche of the economy, its ubiquity and range breathtaking.

lead_paragraph: CANBERRA, Australia — A Chinese defector to Australia who detailed political interference by Beijing. A businessman found dead after telling the authorities about a Chinese plot to install him in Parliament. Suspicious men following critics of Beijing in major Australian cities.

abstract: A mantra for the next 24 hours: Everything is going to be all right.
snippet: A mantra for the next 24 hours: Everything is going to be all right.
lead_paragraph: Good morning. We’ll get to the recipes soon enough, to this insanely good macaroni and cheese (above), to Julia Moskin’s hashed brussels sprouts, to gravy instruction and a whole lot more. This is perhaps the time you need recipes most, of any time of year.

headline_main: A Few Words of Thanksgiving Advice

abstract: As they prepared for “Der Rosenkavalier” at the Met, the mezzo-soprano Magdalena Kozena and the conductor Simon Rattle joined musicians for a chamber concert.
snippet: As they prepared for “Der Rosenkavalier” at the Met, the mezzo-soprano Magdalena Kozena and the conductor Simon Rattle joined musicians for a chamber concert.
lead_paragraph: It’s not unusual for star singers rehearsing at the Metropolitan Opera to make time for a recital while they’re in New York. But the results are not always this interesting.

abstract: In 1964, with “Seven Up!” Michael Apted stumbled into making what has become the most profound documentary series in the history of cinema. Fifty-five years later, the project is reaching its conclusion.
snippet: In 1964, with “Seven Up!” Michael Apted stumbled into making what has become the most profound documentary series in the history of cinema. Fifty-five years later, the project is reaching its conclusion.
lead_paragraph: On a brisk Saturday morning, one uncommonly cloudless and bright for late autumn on England’s moody North Sea coast, the filmmaker Michael Apted paced a sloping headland of mud and stubble with an air of fretful preoccupation. Though the day’s shoot would amount, in the end, to an additional five-minute increment of the documentary project that had intermittently consumed the entirety of his working life, these occasions never ceased to surprise and unnerve him. He had known Jackie, whose arrival was imminent, for 56 years, but her interviews could be volatile, and this one was particularly important, he felt, to get right.
